MOTIONS FOR PAPERS TRANS-CANADA HIGHWAY

Mr. Argue:

For a copy of all letters. telegrams and other communications exchanged between the government of Canada and the provincial governments from January 1, 1948 to date, concerning the construction of a trans-Canada highway.

Mr. MacKinnon: So far as we are con- cerned we are glad to have this order pass, but there appear to be conﬁdential letters from some of the provinces, and I should like ﬁrst to clear those letters with the prov- inces. In the meantime the order might pass.

Mr. Speaker: Carried with the reservation made by the minister.

INCOME TAX—RURAL TELEPHONE COMPANIES

NATIONAL CAPITAL PLANNING

Mr. Diefenbaker:

For a copy of the architect‘s plan for the national capital project together with all letters and com— munications relative to the area thereof and the estimated cost of (a) acquiring the necessary lands; (b) removal of buildings thereon and all other anticipated costs and expenditures.

Mr. St. Laurent: I believe there is no objection to the motion, but I should like to state what I understand from it, to see it that is what the hon. member has in mind. The architect’s plan to which he refers is presumably the report of Mr. Greber, who is the consultant of the national capital planning committee. That report has not yet been approved by the national capital plan- ning committee, nor has it been submitted to the government. It is expected shortly, and as soon as it is received it will be tabled.

[Mr. Caouette.]

COMMONS

The motion refers to the area of the national capital project. As far as the area is concerned, there may be some confusion between the area it was felt desirable to designate as the national capital area for the purpose of establishing a framework within which planning could be carried on, and the parcels of land which it may be thought desirable to acquire for government build— ings, driveways, and so forth. The national capital area is a large region, and has signiﬁ- cance for purposes of planning, but there is no thought that it would ever be acquired in totality by the federal government.

We would understand that the letters and communications sought are in relation to the deﬁnition of the national capital planning area, while the estimates of costs are in rela— tion to the lands of which the project recom- mends the acquisition. If that is what the hon. member wishes to have tabled, I Will see to it that the report is prepared at the earliest possible moment.

Mr. Diefenbaker: Mr. Speaker, what the Prime Minister has stated represents gener- ally the purpose of my request. I should like to ascertain, though, if I may, when the report of Mr. Greber may be expected. There is a great deal of interest in it. I understand that a committee has been sit- ting in Ottawa from time to time in connec— tion with the matter, and it seems to me the time has come for the Prime Minister to make a statement to the house and to the country.

Mr. St. Laurent: I will communicate with the chairman of the national capital planning committee and tell him it is the desire of the members of the house to have this document at the earliest possible moment.

Motion agreed to.
